@Steve L 

It took me a minute, but if you think of "for" as a noun, not a preposition, it makes sense.

I'd prefer a more obviously funny or clever title but I'm not nearly creative enough to come up with one.

@john ezra 

I can’t remember the date.  But it was the United States map one that had the state park answers in the corresponding areas, and the revealer was a great Schrodingers puzzle.  

That one

@Red Carpet 

I remember that puzzle and it is a worthy candidate. I'll try to find it. 

Thanks for checking in, you're welcome to nominate more than one!

@john ezra 

There are others but what comes foremost to mind at the moment when I can't really look back in the archives right now is, 8/28, Jesse Goldberg for its words in phrases. It filled me with complete glee and every time I think about it I still feel gleeful! Many puzzles make me happy but glee is a whole nother level!

Thanks to @B for helping me keep the date and constructor name in mind. ☺️

@Vaer 

TIL, thanks to your comment, that "paeon" was a word at all.

Not a very common word, though.

@Steve L 

“Paeon”  new to me, too. I looked it up last night and have already forgotten what it means. 

And autocorrect doesn’t like it.

@Steve L
You had the advantage of having taught Spanish for umpteen years.

@coloradoz
I had a 20-something day long streak, mostly because the last couple of Saturdays hadn't been that difficult.  And I had to remind myself that I don't care about streaks before I finally hit Reveal.

@B Try xwstats.com.  It will quickly let you  know whether smugness is appropriate.  The median solve time for this puzzle is currently 21:34.  For this week here are the reported global stats, Monday through Saturday with difficulty based on global average in parens:  5:09 (average), 6:59 (average), 11:26 (average), 11:46 (very easy), 11:13 (very easy), 17:24 (easy).

This site only reports stats from those who have joined, and the times may biased toward more experienced solvers. I don't really know. 

Personally my times were more than 20% faster for Wednesday's through Saturday's crosswords.

@TMD 

I assume that most of the people who have accounts at xwstats.com are faster solvers. 

Typically, the median solving time increases the further it is from the time of publication. When I looked just now, the median time for Sunday’s puzzle was 22:36.

@Al  in Pittsburgh 
Last August I had my 90th birthday, and I already have more cognitive function monitors than I would like.  I find it reassuring that I still do Mini in under a minute, but I suspect that I'm not much of a whiz timewise on The Crossword anymore.

(And let's not even talk about typos.)

@dutchiris 
I totally agree. 
Enjoying the constructor's craft is far more fun.

@Sam Lyons 

Here’s the first definition of RITUAL in my dictionary: A ceremony in which the actions and wording follow a prescribed form and order.

The clue seems fine to me.

@Sam Lyons @Andrzej @Steve L @Bill

Thanks for this discussion.  The intersection of language and social behavior is certainly of interest in Wordplay.

Btw, Sam, my New Year's Resolution Shakespeare project floundered, (foundered?), after five plays. Foundered seems more permanent and more accurate.

@Bill and Eric H. 

Not so much discomfort as just seeing an opportunity for discussion. Which I got—in spades!—and was very happy to see. 

@Al 

I hope you haven’t given up on Shakespeare. Anyone who reads him as closely as you do ought to be legally compelled to continue doing so. Did you not enjoy it?

I abandoned revisiting Shakespeare after you and I read As You Like It: Life stuff went supernova and I don’t think I’ve read anything for pleasure in six months. As I sit here in Northern European gloom, however, settling in for an even-longer-and-darker-than-in-Seattle winter, I’m thinking I might revisit reading for pleasure. They say life in the Old World gives you a chance to smell the roses—or so they claimed when they talked me into the teaching gig out here. We’ll see. For now it’s just life with way too many roundabouts. Seems like something the French would have wrought upon humanity.

@Sam Lyons,

Now I’m curious.  At the risk of extending what has to be the Thread of the Year (hello, John Ezra!), I just have to ask, if you don’t mind sharing:

Where are you now?

